commentBody:
@Ed

I would love to support a union if I had any hope for the Union, and maybe I’m being dramatic but I think the Union is undone.

Hope I’m wrong.

@Barry Ancona 

What, no lecture about OPE appearing 88 times in the Shortz Era? 
:D

@Steve L

Good point.

I hope you see that the method is often used to put puzzle critics in their place.

@Steve L 

This one got through, but then I tried to post the continuation of my other post as a reply here.  No such luck...

What is going on here?  Not violating any rules...

@Barry Ancona 
Yesterday it let me have a one-word reply post!
The word was Joel, correcting my Joe typo, maybe that was why. 😸

@B 

He doesn't know.  Short messages have gotten by all along.

Long messages got stopped, all along.

@Steve L 

"But I won't be there to rescue you when you fall off your flat earth."

Gee, it really must be terrible to be disrespected.  I don't know how that feels, Galileo.

@B 

I know it did. I just wanted the two to be together to avoid making people scour the comments for it. 

And I imagine that any minute now, six instances of my original part two, worded slightly differently, will also appear magically.

@Steve L 

Just guessing, but for many, abstaining from the puzzle is a symbolic gesture in support of the union. It's a morality kind of thing.

Would you renew your subscription if it expired tomorrow?

@Mr Dave 

Probably, since my subscription renews automatically, and I wouldn't know until after it happens.  Would it bother me?  Probably not.

I worked for 40 years as a union member (United Federation of Teachers) and never once had to go out on a job action, although I am grateful for those brave teachers who did in the 60s to create the professional environment I worked in (and messed up my eighth grade quite a bit).  Had I ever had to do so, I wouldn't have cared if parents chose to send their schools anyway (in the 60s, they were kept open for those who needed child care).  After all, it would be the teachers' absence that mattered, not the students'.

@Grant 

"I just wish I'd been watching MSNBC when they had to call Pennsylvania."

Apparently the call for civility and politeness doesn't extend to taunting from the right.

@Sam Corbin 

Here’s the thing: the belief that you can compartmentalize this is wrong.  This is the slippery slope and you are encouraging “all” to be the ostrich sticking its head in the sand. Trying to treat this as unconnected from the other  things in our lives that matter to us has enabled this. It is only going to get worse if we continue to try to normalize this by shifting it to an “other” category. Shame on anyone who enables this by doing that.  Play your games, watch your movies, consume your drugs, whatever, and you are enabling the fourth reich.

Shame on you.

@Jennifer
I could not disagree more.
I don’t know where you work, but if your boss starts mistreating you I’ll stop shopping there.

@Norwood 

It was more than a setback.  

It was a wholesale repudiation of everything America is supposed to stand for.

@Charles Nelson Reilly 

I wish I could wake you up from this nightmare... 

I can't, but I hope it's enough to let you know that you are not alone.
